{
  "id": "cleanorlabs/developer-reference-datasets",
  "title": "Developer Reference: Aspect, WCAG, MIME, Encoding",
  "subtitle": "Computed lookup tables: aspect-ratio pixels, WCAG contrast, UTF byte sizes",
  "description": "Open, reproducible reference tables that web and app developers look up constantly \u2014 computed from first principles, not scraped, so every value is exact and re-runnable. CC BY 4.0.\n\nQuick answers inside:\n- Aspect ratios: 16:9 is 1920x1080, 1280x720, 3840x2160; 9:16 (Stories/Reels/TikTok) is those flipped. 16 named ratios x 11 widths + 29 named resolutions.\n- WCAG contrast: AA needs 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large, AAA 7:1. Contrast ratio + AA/AAA pass-fail for every pair of a 25-colour UI palette (600 pairs) and each colour vs white/black.\n- File types: extension -> MIME type + magic-number signature WITH byte offset (RIFF/ISO-BMFF/tar signatures are NOT at byte 0, which most magic-byte lists get wrong). 66 types.\n- Encoding sizes: a Latin char is 1 UTF-8 byte, accented/Greek/Cyrillic 2, CJK 3, most emoji 4; a flag emoji is 8 bytes and 2 code points. UTF-8/16/32 per script.\n- QR capacity: a version-1 QR holds 41 digits / 25 alphanumeric / 17 bytes at ECC L; up to 7,089 digits at version 40. Computed from ISO/IEC 18004, verified against the published table.\n- Format support: AVIF is fully supported since Chrome 85 / Firefox 93 / Safari 16.4; JPEG XL is fully supported nowhere. 6 formats x 8 browsers.\n\nEvery table is generated by a small script in the repo, checkable against any online tool.\n\nCite: DOI 10.5281/zenodo.21369536 (CC BY 4.0, Cleanor Labs).\nCode & methodology: https://github.com/cleanor-app/developer-reference-datasets\nHuman write-ups: https://cleanor.app/research/open-datasets",
  "licenses": [
    {
      "name": "CC BY 4.0"
    }
  ],
  "keywords": [
    "computer science",
    "data analytics",
    "beginner",
    "tabular",
    "internet"
  ],
